    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1843-07-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1843-07-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="33"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d33">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Everett</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Legare</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 44.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1843-07-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 1, 1843</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">H. S. Legare</hi>, Esq.,<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State:</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>:</p>
                <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                <p>With respect to the occupation of the Sandwich Islands, I have reason to think
                    that the conduct of Lord George Paulet in coercing their provisional cession to
                    this Government has been formally disavowed. I am to see Lord Aberdeen this
                    afternoon and hope to ascertain positively whether this is the case. If I find
                    that the cession is not and is not likely to be disavowed, I shall address a
                    pointed remonstrance to this Government against the occupation and spare no
                    pains to enlist in the same course the representatives of the other maritime
                    powers. Mr. Marshall of Charlestown (Massachusetts) arrived here yesterday, with
                    authority from the King of the Sandwich Islands, as a joint commissioner with
                    Mr. Richards. He is the bearer of dispatches from the Government of the islands
                    to that of Great Britain. He has been preceded by Mr. Simpson, the deputy consul
                    left in the islands by the late British consul, Mr. Charlton. * * * Mr. Simpson
                    came to London, a few days since, as bearer of Lord George Pauleys dispatches to
                    the admiralty.</p>
                <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                <p>I am, sir, respectfully, your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edward Everett.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
